to get to because it's a direct train from Southampton. There are lots of hotels around if you don't want

91
00:07:53,660 --> 00:07:58,880
to stay in the con hotel, but there's plenty of room in the con hotel if you do. And it's generally a very

92
00:07:58,880 --> 00:08:01,920
good location. So I am excited to go in 2021.

93
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:07,520
I just want to go to an Eastercon anywhere, anytime, ever again. Oh, sorry.

94
00:08:07,520 --> 00:08:09,700
Not Easter? I mean...

95
00:08:09,700 --> 00:08:14,460
One of the things that surprised me about the bid session was there was a question about what would

96
00:08:14,460 --> 00:08:19,680
happen if COVID-19 meant that there were still travel restrictions in place at Easter next year.

97
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:24,800
And the concom said that they hadn't really thought about that and hadn't put any plans in place.

98
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:28,620
What do you think about that? Do you think that's sensible?

99
00:08:28,620 --> 00:08:36,060
I was appalled by how little planning they did this year. I mean, obviously, having to cancel

100
00:08:36,060 --> 00:08:43,780
your Eastercon is terrible. But I feel that they could have done a lot more in the four weeks or

101
00:08:43,780 --> 00:08:49,380
five weeks between when they cancelled and the original dates to make sure that virtual events

102
00:08:49,380 --> 00:08:54,560
were happening and were encouraged, even if they hadn't done all the work of organising them

103
00:08:54,560 --> 00:08:59,300
themselves. What they actually did was sent out a thing saying, please don't organise any events

104
00:08:59,300 --> 00:09:05,060
because we're going to let you know, which was the exact opposite of what I think they should have

105
00:09:05,060 --> 00:09:11,720
done. I understand that if it had been my Eastercon being cancelled, I might have been too busy

106
00:09:11,720 --> 00:09:18,120
crying into my beer to think about what alternatives we could have. But it would have been quite

107
00:09:18,120 --> 00:09:25,160
straightforward to have set up social spaces, to have set a system in place so that panels could have

108
00:09:25,160 --> 00:09:30,860
happened, to say, we're going to have some chats about some topics you might be interested in that

109
00:09:30,860 --> 00:09:35,760
you could sign up to be on a panel on or something like that. And they could have done all of that and

110
00:09:35,760 --> 00:09:41,040
they didn't do any of it. And that was for this year. So I was very keen to say Eastercons or all

111
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:46,780
conventions in the future should have some planning arrangements for this sort of thing and should be

112
00:09:46,780 --> 00:09:52,520
planning to do virtual things so that they could switch if they need to. And I was surprised that

113
00:09:52,520 --> 00:10:00,020
they didn't. I feel that they missed an opportunity. I feel that although, as they said, doing it properly

114
00:10:00,020 --> 00:10:06,900
can be quite expensive, you can do it improperly with not a lot of work, as we've all discovered in the last

115
00:10:06,900 --> 00:10:12,640
six weeks. I think I'm not surprised that they didn't do anything because I think that it was very clearly a big shock to everyone that this developed as quickly as it did. Like intellectually, I knew it was going to, but sort of emotionally, I think it really hit me that like, this is the first Easter for a very long time that I've not gone to an Eastercon. So that was a bit of a shock to the system. And so I think I can understand why they might not have been able to arrange anything this time round. And I

116
00:10:12,640 --> 00:10:19,380
It was very clearly a big shock to everyone that this developed as quickly as it did.

117
00:10:19,380 --> 00:10:28,960
Like intellectually, I knew it was going to, but sort of emotionally, I think it really hit me that like this is the first Easter for a very long time that I've not gone to an Easter con.

118
00:10:28,960 --> 00:10:30,740
So that was a bit of a shock to the system.

119
00:10:30,740 --> 00:10:35,820
And so I think I can understand why they might not have been able to arrange anything this time around.

120
00:10:35,820 --> 00:10:38,040
And I appreciate that's a very hard thing.

121
00:10:38,040 --> 00:10:40,160
And I appreciate that that could have been very fraught.

122
00:10:40,560 --> 00:10:49,700
What I am sort of hoping is that if there are still travel restrictions next year, we don't end up in a situation where, again, we have no official Easter con provision.

123
00:10:49,700 --> 00:11:01,700
Because I don't want to end up in a situation where this kind of thing happens again with no official panels or official social spaces or anything like that.

124
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:07,160
I think I can understand and sympathize with what happened this year.

125
00:11:07,480 --> 00:11:17,100
I think if you are planning to do Easter con next year, it is just prudent to assume that you are not going to know until closer time how it's going to work.

126
00:11:17,100 --> 00:11:23,920
I think it's just prudent to plan for if you have to do a remote Easter con or if you want to even include some remote options.

127
00:11:23,920 --> 00:11:29,340
Because clearly the last thing that's going to come back is large gatherings of people.

128
00:11:29,480 --> 00:11:33,420
And the last thing that's going to come back is long distance travel.

129
00:11:33,420 --> 00:11:36,640
So you might be in the position where we can have a full Easter con.

130
00:11:36,640 --> 00:11:39,040
You might be in the position where you have a reduced Easter con.

131
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:40,920
Or you might be in the position where you have no Easter con.

132
00:11:40,920 --> 00:11:44,500
And I think it's at this point you just have to have contingency plans for those.

133
00:11:45,080 --> 00:11:53,620
And if you don't, then you're going to have another year of planning to run a great convention and then being extremely disappointed if you can't do that.

134
00:11:53,800 --> 00:12:05,400
I think there is a fourth option, which is that they may have a lot of members who, even if travel is allowed and the Easter con is allowed, have decided for themselves that it's not safe to do so.

135
00:12:05,640 --> 00:12:20,000
And I think the notion that we might disenfranchise our oldest and in poorest health members, not because they can't physically get to the convention, but that we don't think that they don't think it's safe for them to do so.

136
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:25,620
And that even with a year's warning, nobody's doing anything about that.

137
00:12:25,620 --> 00:12:29,200
And when they were asked the question, we're kind of like, well, we've got no plans to do anything about that.

138
00:12:29,200 --> 00:12:33,040
I feel like there's a lot more that could be done here.

139
00:12:33,560 --> 00:12:44,640
I agree. And I think it will be really interesting to see what does happen next year, because obviously I think all three of us are very much hoping that Easter con will happen and everything will be normal and there will be none of this that needs to be worried about.

140
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:51,020
But I am keenly aware that me hoping that happens and it's actually happening are two very different things.

141
00:12:51,020 --> 00:13:03,540
I think the other interesting point here is that, especially with Worldcon, but with Easter con as well, I think the idea of having panels one can access virtually,

142
00:13:03,540 --> 00:13:12,300
from the perspective of being able to buy a supporting membership and do that is something that has been being talked about more and more in recent years.

143
00:13:12,720 --> 00:13:18,760
And I am wondering whether this will be a shove towards trying to start making that happen.

144
00:13:18,760 --> 00:13:30,160
And I am hoping that this is the shove that starts making that happen, because I often find myself in situations at Easter cons where I end up missing a panel that I would love to go back and see a recording of,

145
00:13:30,420 --> 00:13:39,380
or I end up being on a panel where I would love to watch it back because I think there were some really interesting points made and I'm not able to take notes as thoroughly as I'd like to while talking.

146
00:13:39,900 --> 00:13:47,080
So I think it would be really nice if we could develop that capability and this seems like a good, almost like a good excuse to try and do that.

147
00:13:47,080 --> 00:13:51,320
Do you two think that this will be an impetus towards that?

148
00:13:51,320 --> 00:13:53,040
Do you think I'm being overly optimistic?

149
00:13:53,040 --> 00:13:54,720
I think you're right.

150
00:13:54,720 --> 00:14:01,100
I think that everyone would like more things to be streamed, live broadcast recorded for later consumption.

151
00:14:01,240 --> 00:14:15,180
And this could be a good opportunity because the benefit here is that you could plan your convention panel so they can either happen live at the Easter con with a streaming broadcast or they can happen live from people's houses with a streaming broadcast.

152
00:14:15,180 --> 00:14:19,140
And then in either situation, you are already prepared.

153
00:14:19,140 --> 00:14:25,320
I think the best way to do this is to have some of the panels planned that way.

154
00:14:25,460 --> 00:14:44,120
So rather than saying we're going to try and recreate the 420 items at an Easter con or whatever, we've got a lot, which includes all sorts of items which nobody in their right minds will put on the internet, along with all sorts of things where actually the audience for them is very small.

155
00:14:44,120 --> 00:14:46,520
I think the latter sort are fine.

156
00:14:46,520 --> 00:14:52,160
You know, you may only get 10 people tuning in, but those people really care and they're all over the world.

157
00:14:52,160 --> 00:14:59,560
So I think there is something there about you can do certain sorts of things better in small groups, including an internet presence.

158
00:14:59,560 --> 00:15:15,340
And if you just said, well, we won't be doing all of it, but we're going to focus on, say, half a dozen really high profile events that we'll do online and a few small and very specialist events that we'll do online.

159
00:15:15,340 --> 00:15:18,980
And the rest of the stuff will happen if it happens and not if it doesn't.

160
00:15:18,980 --> 00:15:20,620
I think that's very true.

161
00:15:20,620 --> 00:15:27,560
And actually, I spent two days this week doing two full day training calls, which all took place on Zoom.

162
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:29,500
And it was incredibly tiring.

163
00:15:29,500 --> 00:15:32,680
And I would never voluntarily do that for an Easter con.

164
00:15:32,680 --> 00:15:35,020
So you don't need to stream 420 items.

165
00:15:35,020 --> 00:15:36,880
You need to stream 20.

166
00:15:36,880 --> 00:15:38,140
Maximum, yeah.

167
00:15:38,140 --> 00:15:45,720
Because I think if I was going to do that, I would be streaming the big Guests of Honor panels and talks.

168
00:15:46,280 --> 00:15:53,040
Because oftentimes what happens is I'm torn between an interesting little niche item and the interview with John Scalzi.

169
00:15:53,040 --> 00:16:02,320
And if you stream the interview with John Scalzi, John Scalzi is already going to be on his best behavior because he is in that kind of work mode as a Guests of Honor anyway.

170
00:16:02,840 --> 00:16:06,620
And it means I can go to a small little niche panel that I otherwise wouldn't have been able to attend.

171
00:16:06,620 --> 00:16:14,440
So I do think there is an argument there that you can get around that by only streaming the big panels where you're already hedging your bets a bit.

172
00:16:14,720 --> 00:16:22,780
The other thing I will say is that I think that at the moment we have panels that are more intimate because we know they're not being recorded.

173
00:16:22,780 --> 00:16:31,220
And I think if you start recording panels, you will get a slight shift in what people are willing to say if they know they're being recorded, which I think would change the complexion of panels slightly.

174
00:16:31,660 --> 00:16:39,080
It is interesting to note, I think I saw one of the people who worked on Con Zealand saying that prior to the announcement they were going virtual,

175
00:16:39,080 --> 00:16:44,920
only five people who had filled out the program survey had said that they did not want to be recorded.

176
00:16:44,920 --> 00:16:48,360
So I think most people appearing on panels are willing to be recorded.

177
00:16:48,360 --> 00:16:54,800
I think as long as they know it's going to happen in advance and can tailor their presence on that panel with that knowledge.

178
00:16:54,800 --> 00:17:02,220
I do think in some ways you'd lose a lot if you streamed the entire program, but I wouldn't necessarily think that would be necessary.

179
00:17:02,220 --> 00:17:06,520
Although I will say if it was only available to supporting and attending members,

180
00:17:06,520 --> 00:17:15,040
I think I wonder to what extent I would be worried about guarding my speech because if I know that anyone at the Eastercon can watch my speech back,

181
00:17:15,040 --> 00:17:20,100
that's not much more public than anyone at the Eastercon being able to come into my panel.

182
00:17:20,100 --> 00:17:20,880
But I don't know.

183
00:17:20,880 --> 00:17:25,740
Anybody at the Eastercon who has recording technology can then pass it on.

184
00:17:25,740 --> 00:17:29,540
In practice, everyone can record all the time anyway.

185
00:17:29,540 --> 00:17:32,260
You know, we've not really...

186
00:17:32,260 --> 00:17:35,320
People are very polite about asking if they can record panels.

187
00:17:36,120 --> 00:17:38,360
But anyone with a phone can record a panel.

